<h2>Retatrutide: The Triple-Action Leader</h2>

<div class="cd cb">
  <div class="tg">Top Pick</div>
  <h3>Retatrutide (LY-3437943)</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;"><strong>Type:</strong> Triple receptor agonist (GLP-1, GIP, Glucagon) &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Dose Range:</strong> 2&ndash;12 mg weekly &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Route:</strong> Subcutaneous injection &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Developer:</strong> Eli Lilly &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Stage:</strong> Phase 3 clinical trials &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Best For:</strong> Maximum fat loss with muscle preservation</p>
</div>

<p>When researchers at Eli Lilly set out to improve on tirzepatide, they aimed for something unprecedented: a single molecule that hits three key metabolic receptors at once. The result was <a href="/articles/retatrutide-complete-guide">retatrutide</a>, which engages GLP-1, GIP, and glucagon receptors in one package.</p>

<p>Clinical trial participants averaged 24% body weight reduction over 48 weeks (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37385275/">Jastreboff et al., 2023</a>). That's a number that was unimaginable five years ago.</p>

<p>What makes retatrutide stand apart isn't just the weight loss numbers. The glucagon component provides a metabolic boost that prevents the metabolic slowdown often seen with pure appetite suppressants.</p>

<p>The GIP activity also helps maintain lean muscle mass during weight loss. It's this balanced approach that has made retatrutide the preferred choice among metabolic specialists for patients needing significant transformation.</p>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Key Finding</div>
  <p>Retatrutide's triple-agonist mechanism produced greater weight loss than tirzepatide (dual) or semaglutide (single) in matched populations. The glucagon receptor activation drives additional energy expenditure beyond appetite suppression alone.</p>
</div>

